<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Computing SVD with NumPy</h3>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To compute the SVD of a matrix using numpy,=
 you can call the function <code>[np.linalg.svd](https://numpy.org/doc/stab=
le/reference/generated/numpy.linalg.svd.html)</code>. Given a matrix <em>A<=
/em> with shape (<em>m</em>, <em>n</em>), the function returns a tuple (<em=
>U</em>, <em>S</em>, <em>V=E1=B5=97</em>), where <em>U</em> is a matrix wit=
h shape (<em>m</em>, <em>m</em>) containing the left- singular vectors in i=
ts columns, <em>S</em> is a vector of size <em>k</em> =3D <strong> min_(_m,=
 </strong> n) containing the singular values in descending order, an<em>d</=
em> V=E1=B5=97 is a matrix with shape __ (<em>n</em>, n) containing the rig=
ht singular vectors in its rows.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, let=E2=80=99s use this functio=
n to compute the SVD of the matrix from the previous example:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python"><span class=3D"token keyword">import</span> nu=
mpy <span class=3D"token keyword">as</span> np

A <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> np<span class=3D"token punctuat=
ion">.</span>array<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span><span class=3D"=
token punctuation">[</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">[</span><span =
class=3D"token number">1</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <=
span class=3D"token number">0</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">]</sp=
an><span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <span class=3D"token punctuat=
ion">[</span><span class=3D"token number">0</span><span class=3D"token punc=
tuation">,</span> <span class=3D"token number">1</span><span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">]</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <span clas=
s=3D"token punctuation">[</span><span class=3D"token number">2</span><span =
class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <span class=3D"token number">2</span><=
span class=3D"token punctuation">]</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">=
]</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
np<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>linalg<span class=3D"token punc=
tuation">.</span>svd<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>A<span class=
=3D"token punctuation">)</span></code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The output we get is:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">(array([[-2.35702260e-01,  7.07106781e-0=
1, -6.66666667e-01],
        [-2.35702260e-01, -7.07106781e-01, -6.66666667e-01],
        [-9.42809042e-01, -1.11022302e-16,  3.33333333e-01]]),
 array([3., 1.]),
 array([[-0.70710678, -0.70710678],
        [ 0.70710678, -0.70710678]]))</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">This is the same SVD decomposition we have =
obtained with our manual computation, up to a sign difference (e.g., the fi=
rst column of <em>U</em> has flipped direction). This shows that an SVD dec=
omposition of a matrix is not entirely unique. While the singular values th=
emselves are unique, the associated singular vectors (i.e., the columns of =
<em>U</em> and <em>V</em>) are not strictly unique due to the following rea=
sons:</p>
<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li>If a singular value is repeated, the corresponding singular vectors can=
 be chosen to be any orthonormal set that spans the associated eigenspace.<=
/li>
<li>Even if the singular values are distinct, the corresponding singular ve=
ctors can be multiplied by -1 (i.e., their direction can be flipped) and st=
ill form a valid SVD.</li>
</ol>
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Compact SVD</h2>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The compact singular value decomposition is=
 a reduced form of the full SVD, which retains only the non-zero singular v=
alues and their corresponding singular vectors.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Formally, the compact SVD of an <em>m</em> =
=C3=97 <em>n</em> matrix <em>A</em> with rank <em>r</em> (<em>r</em> =E2=89=
=A4 min{<em>m</em>, <em>n</em>}) is a factorization of the form <em>A</em> =
=3D _U=E1=B5=A3_=CE=A3<em>=E1=B5=A3V=E1=B5=A3=E1=B5=97</em>, where:</p>
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><em>U=E1=B5=A3</em> is an <em>m</em> =C3=97 <em>r</em> matrix whose col=
umns are the first <em>r</em> left-singular vectors of <em>A</em>.</li>
<li>=CE=A3<em>=E1=B5=A3</em> is an <em>r</em> =C3=97 <em>r</em> diagonal ma=
trix with the <em>r</em> non-zero singular values on the diagonal.</li>
<li><em>V=E1=B5=A3</em> is an <em>n</em> =C3=97 <em>r</em> matrix whose col=
umns are the first <em>r</em> right-singular vectors of <em>A</em>.</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, the rank of the matrix from ou=
r previous example is 2, since it has two non-zero singular values. Therefo=
re, its compact SVD decomposition is:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f5f=
5f5" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f5f5f5;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1684" height=3D"266" class=3D"wp=
-image-508488 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/19AxgF-Pm-ZDn7jj98NX97g.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The matrices <em>U=E1=B5=A3</em>, =CE=A3<em=
>=E1=B5=A3</em> and <em>V=E1=B5=A3</em> contain only the essential informat=
ion needed to reconstruct the matrix <em>A</em>. The compact SVD can yield =
significant savings in storage and computation, especially for matrices wit=
h many zero singular values (i.e., when <em>r</em> &lt;&lt; min{<em>m</em>,=
 <em>n</em>}).</p>
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Truncated SVD</h2>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Truncated (reduced) SVD is a variation of S=
VD used for approximating the original matrix <em>A</em> with a matrix of a=
 lower rank.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To create a truncated SVD of a matrix <em>A=
</em> with rank <em>r</em>, we take only the <em>k</em> &lt; <em>r</em> lar=
gest singular values and their corresponding singular vectors (<em>k</em> i=
s a parameter). This gives us an approximation of the original matrix <em>A=
=E2=82=96</em> =3D _U=E2=82=96_=CE=A3<em>=E2=82=96V=E2=82=96=E1=B5=97</em>,=
 where:</p>
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><em>U=E2=82=96</em> is an <em>m</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> matrix whose col=
umns are the first <em>k</em> left-singular vectors of <em>A</em>, correspo=
nding to the <em>k</em> largest singular values.</li>
<li>=CE=A3<em>=E2=82=96</em> is an <em>k</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> diagonal ma=
trix with the <em>k</em> largest __ singular values on the diagonal.</li>
<li><em>V=E2=82=96</em> is an <em>n</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> matrix whose col=
umns are the first <em>k</em> right-singular vectors of <em>A</em>, <strong=
> corresponding to the </strong> k largest singular values.</li>
</ul>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f3e=
4ec" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f3e4ec;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"2064" height=3D"582" class=3D"wp=
-image-508489 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1CHNj_GwtRum0kz7QLu4Jwg.png" alt=3D"Truncated SVD"><f=
igcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Truncated SVD</figcaption></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, we can truncate the matrix fro=
m the previous example to have a rank of <em>k</em> =3D 1 by taking only th=
e largest single value and its corresponding vectors:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f5f=
5f5" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f5f5f5;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1713" height=3D"252" class=3D"wp=
-image-508490 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1ng13MjdQSvOERhFefv1pXw.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">In NumPy, the truncated SVD can be easily c=
omputed using the following code snippet:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">U<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> S<=
span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> Vt <span class=3D"token operator"=
>=3D</span> np<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>linalg<span class=
=3D"token punctuation">.</span>svd<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span=
>A<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>

k <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> <span class=3D"token number">1<=
/span>  <span class=3D"token comment"># target rank</span>
U_k <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> U<span class=3D"token punctua=
tion">[</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">:</span><span class=3D"toke=
n punctuation">,</span> <span class=3D"token punctuation">:</span>k<span cl=
ass=3D"token punctuation">]</span>
S_k <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> np<span class=3D"token punctu=
ation">.</span>diag<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>S<span class=
=3D"token punctuation">[</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">:</span>k<=
span class=3D"token punctuation">]</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">=
)</span>
Vt_k <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> Vt<span class=3D"token punct=
uation">[</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">:</span>k<span class=3D"t=
oken punctuation">,</span> <span class=3D"token punctuation">:</span><span =
class=3D"token punctuation">]</span>

A_k <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> U_k @ S_k @ Vt_k
A_k</code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">array([[0.5, 0.5],
       [0.5, 0.5],
       [2. , 2. ]])</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Truncated SVD is particularly effective, si=
nce the truncated matrix <em>A=E2=82=96</em> is the best rank-<em>k</em> ap=
proximation of the matrix <em>A</em> in terms of both the Frobenius norm (t=
he least squares difference) and the 2-norm, i.e.,</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"faf=
afa" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fafafa;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1374" height=3D"121" class=3D"wp=
-image-508491 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1a4uc2LYx6WS8GPzkdcZkmg.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">This result is known as the <strong>Eckart-=
Young-Mirsky theorem</strong> or the matrix approximation lemma, and its pr=
oof can be found in this <a href=3D"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Low-rank_=
approximation">Wikipedia page</a>.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The choice of <em>k</em> controls the trade=
off between approximation accuracy and the compactness of the representatio=
n. A smaller <em>k</em> results in a more compact matrix but a rougher appr=
oximation. In real-world data matrices, only a very small subset of the sin=
gular values are large. In such cases, <em>A=E2=82=96</em> can be a very go=
od approximation of <em>A</em> by retaining the few singular values that ar=
e large.</p>
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Dimensionality Reduction with Truncated SVD<=
/h3>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Using the truncated SVD, it is also possibl=
e to reduce the number of dimensions (features) in the data matrix <em>A</e=
m>. To reduce the dimensionality of <em>A</em> from <em>n</em> to <em>k</em=
>, we project the matrix rows onto the space spanned by the first <em>k</em=
> right-singular vectors. This is done by multiplying the original data mat=
rix <em>A</em> by the matrix <em>V=E2=82=96</em>:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"fbf=
bfb" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fbfbfb;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1609" height=3D"96" class=3D"wp-=
image-508492 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/1bG9g4YY1hh1zpBc9_b6o6w.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The reduced matrix now has dimensions <em>n=
</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> and contains the projection of the original data on=
to the <em>k</em>-dimensional subspace. Its columns are the new features in=
 the reduced dimensional space. These features are linear combinations of t=
he original features and are orthogonal to each other.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Using our previous example, we can reduce t=
he number of dimensions of our data matrix <em>A</em> from 2 to 1 as follow=
s:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f6f=
6f6" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f6f6f6;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1894" height=3D"244" class=3D"wp=
-image-508493 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1btx3a_6RQ2RQp7curQeYeA.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Another way to compute the reduced matrix i=
s based on the following observation:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"fbf=
bfb" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fbfbfb;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1581" height=3D"87" class=3D"wp-=
image-508495 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/1FvGm7-FJtaFTjb5suc0PaA.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph"><em>Proof</em>: The full SVD of <em>A</em> =
is <em>A</em> =3D _U_=CE=A3<em>V=E1=B5=97</em>, therefore <em>AV</em> =3D _=
U_=CE=A3. By comparing the <em>j</em>-th columns of each side of the equati=
on we get:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f9f=
9f9" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f9f9f9;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1688" height=3D"84" class=3D"wp-=
image-508496 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/12gghl5WTuSz0FrpOoGttDg.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Therefore, all the columns of <em>AV=E2=82=
=96</em> are equal to all the columns of _U=E2=82=96_=CE=A3<em>=E2=82=96</e=
m>, so the two matrices must be equal.</p>
<hr class=3D"wp-block-separator has-alpha-channel-opacity">
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Using _U=E2=82=96_=CE=A3<em>=E2=82=96</em> =
is a more efficient way to compute the reduced matrix, because it requires =
to multiply matrices of size <em>m</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> and <em>k</em> =
=C3=97 <em>k</em>, instead of matrices of size <em>m</em> =C3=97 <em>n</em>=
 and <em>n</em> =C3=97 <em>k</em> (<em>k</em> is typically much smaller tha=
n <em>n</em>).</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">In our previous example:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f5f=
5f5" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f5f5f5;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1710" height=3D"258" class=3D"wp=
-image-508497 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1lOJPKiQBR7Z91jkdVF_LaA.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Dimensionality reduction using truncated SV=
D is often used as a data preprocessing step before machine learning tasks =
such as classification or clustering, where it helps dealing with the <a hr=
ef=3D"https://medium.com/ai-made-simple/what-is-the-curse-of-dimensionality=
-b9b4b81a25c5">curse of dimensionality</a>, reduce computational costs and =
potentially improve the performance of the machine learning algorithm.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To reduce the dimensionality of new data po=
ints that arrive after the machine learning model has been trained (e.g., s=
amples in the test set), we simply project them onto the same subspace span=
ned by the first <em>k</em> right-singular vectors of <em>A</em>:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f8f=
8f8" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f8f8f8;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1497" height=3D"98" class=3D"wp-=
image-508498 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/1rmY-Vp8eK3GdSFEcfG6A4A.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Recall that our convention is to express ea=
ch vector <strong>x</strong> as a column vector, while data points are stor=
ed as rows of <em>A</em>, which is why we left-multiply <strong>x</strong> =
by <em>V=E2=82=96=E1=B5=97</em> instead of right multiplying it by <em>V=E2=
=82=96</em>.</p>
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Reconstruction Error</h3>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">A key metric in assessing the effectiveness=
 of dimensionality reduction techniques is called the <strong>reconstructio=
n error</strong>. It provides a quantitative measure of the loss of informa=
tion resulting from the reduction process.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To measure the reconstruction error of a sp=
ecific vector, we first project it back onto the original space spanned by =
the <em>m</em> right-singular vectors. This is done by multiplying <em>V=E2=
=82=96</em> by the reduced vector:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"fbf=
bfb" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fbfbfb;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1595" height=3D"94" class=3D"wp-=
image-508499 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/1vL-0zwtXD5jtMWEXWegOew.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We then measure the reconstruction error as=
 the mean squared error (MSE) between the reconstructed components of the v=
ector and the original components:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"faf=
afa" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fafafa;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1611" height=3D"179" class=3D"wp=
-image-508500 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/14bnIECD35lUMV67Ae22yHA.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We can also measure the reconstruction erro=
r of the entire matrix <em>A</em> by projecting the reduced matrix rows bac=
k onto the original space spanned by the <em>m</em> right-singular vectors.=
 This is done by multiplying the reduced <em>A</em> by the transpose of <em=
>V=E2=82=96</em>:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"fbf=
bfb" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #fbfbfb;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1535" height=3D"97" class=3D"wp-=
image-508501 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-con=
tent/uploads/2023/11/1JksmNSslTSUYrwf09rEarg.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We can then use either the MSE between the =
elements of the reconstructed matrix and the original elements, or the Frob=
enius norm of the difference between the two matrices:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f9f=
9fa" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f9f9fa;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1710" height=3D"245" class=3D"wp=
-image-508503 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1r-sxsGYziDjsvcWNnkoTZA.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, the reconstructed matrix of th=
e reduced matrix from our previous example is:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f5f=
5f5" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f5f5f5;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1521" height=3D"242" class=3D"wp=
-image-508504 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1NobsH5g54pvQBe7ZOycNrw.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">And the reconstruction error is:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"f4f=
4f4" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #f4f4f4;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1524" height=3D"106" class=3D"wp=
-image-508505 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1lhZPWiQanLCy1UVU2XPHwg.png" alt=3D""></figure>
<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Truncated SVD in Scikit-Learn</h3>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Scikit-Learn provides an efficient implemen=
tation of truncated SVD in the class <code>[sklearn.decomposition.Truncated=
SVD](https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decompositio=
n.TruncatedSVD.html)</code>. Its important parameters are:</p>
<ul class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><code>n_components</code>: Desired number of dimensions for the output =
data (defaults to 2).</li>
<li>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph"><code>algorithm</code>: The SVD solver to u=
se. Can be one of the following options:</p>
<ol class=3D"wp-block-list">
<li><code>'arppack'</code> uses the <a href=3D"https://docs.scipy.org/doc/s=
cipy/tutorial/arpack.html">ARPACK wrapper</a> in SciPy to compute the eigen=
-decomposition of <em>AA=E1=B5=97</em> or <em>A=E1=B5=97A</em> (whichever i=
s more efficient). ARPACK is an iterative algorithm that efficiently comput=
es a few eigenvalues and eigenvectors of large sparse matrices.</li>
<li><code>'randomized'</code> (the default) uses a fast randomized SVD solv=
er based on an algorithm by Halko et al. [1].</li>
</ol>
</li>
<li><code>n_iter</code>: The number of iterations for the randomized SVD so=
lver (defaults to 5).</li>
</ul>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, let=E2=80=99s demonstrate the =
usage of this class on our matrix from the previous example:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python"><span class=3D"token keyword">from</span> skle=
arn<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>decomposition <span class=3D"t=
oken keyword">import</span> TruncatedSVD

svd <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> TruncatedSVD<span class=3D"to=
ken punctuation">(</span>n_components<span class=3D"token operator">=3D</sp=
an><span class=3D"token number">1</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">,=
</span> random_state<span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span><span class=3D=
"token number">0</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
A_reduced <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> svd<span class=3D"token=
 punctuation">.</span>fit_transform<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</spa=
n>A<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
A_reduced</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The output we get is the reduced matrix:</p=
>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">array([[0.70710678],
       [0.70710678],
       [2.82842712]])</code></pre>
<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading">Example: Image Compression</h2>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Singular value decomposition can be used fo=
r image compression. Although an image matrix is often of full rank, its lo=
wer ranks usually have very small singular values. Thus, truncated SVD can =
lead to a significant reduction in the image size without losing too much i=
nformation.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, we will demonstrate how to use=
 truncated SVD to compress the following image:</p>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"d8c=
fc8" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #d8cfc8;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1911" height=3D"951" class=3D"wp=
-image-508506 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1ajwQslYydCWajGV7Mr0nbw.png" alt=3D"Photo taken by th=
e author"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">Photo taken by the autho=
r</figcaption></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We first load the image into a NumPy array =
using the function <code>[matplotlib.pyplot.imread](https://matplotlib.org/=
stable/api/_as_gen/matplotlib.pyplot.imread.html)</code>:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python"><span class=3D"token keyword">import</span> ma=
tplotlib<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>pyplot <span class=3D"tok=
en keyword">as</span> plt

image <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> plt<span class=3D"token pun=
ctuation">.</span>imread<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span><span cla=
ss=3D"token string">'image.jpg'</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">)</=
span></code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The shape of the image is:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">image<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span=
>shape</code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">(1600, 1200, 3)</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The height of the image is 1600 pixels, its=
 width is 1200 pixels, and it has 3 color channels (RGB).</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Since SVD can only be applied to 2D data, w=
e can either execute it on each color channel separately, or we can reshape=
 the image from a 3D matrix to a 2D matrix by flattening each color channel=
 and stacking them horizontally (or vertically).</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, the following code snippet res=
hapes the image into a 2D matrix by stacking the color channels horizontall=
y:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">height<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</spa=
n> width<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> channels <span class=3D"=
token operator">=3D</span> image<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>s=
hape
flat_image <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> image<span class=3D"to=
ken punctuation">.</span>reshape<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span><=
span class=3D"token operator">-</span><span class=3D"token number">1</span>=
<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> width <span class=3D"token opera=
tor">*</span> channels<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span></code></pr=
e>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The shape of the flattened image is:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">flat_image<span class=3D"token punctuation">.<=
/span>shape</code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">(1600, 3600)</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The rank of the image=E2=80=99s matrix is:<=
/p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">np<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>li=
nalg<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>matrix_rank<span class=3D"tok=
en punctuation">(</span>flat_image<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span=
></code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">1600</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The matrix is of full rank (since min(1600,=
 3600) =3D 1600).</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Let=E2=80=99s plot the first 100 singular v=
alues of the matrix:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">U<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> S<=
span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> Vt <span class=3D"token operator"=
>=3D</span> np<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>linalg<span class=
