<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We can clearly see a rapid decay in the sin=
gular values. This decay means that we can effectively truncate the image w=
ithout a significant loss of accuracy.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">For example, let=E2=80=99s truncate the ima=
ge to have a rank of 100 using Truncated SVD:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">svd <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> =
TruncatedSVD<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>n_components<span cla=
ss=3D"token operator">=3D</span><span class=3D"token number">100</span><spa=
n class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
truncated_image <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> svd<span class=3D=
"token punctuation">.</span>fit_transform<span class=3D"token punctuation">=
(</span>flat_image<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span></code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The shape of the truncated image is:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">truncated_image<span class=3D"token punctuatio=
n">.</span>shape</code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">(1600, 100)</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">The size of the truncated image is only 100=
/3600 =3D 2.78% of the original image!</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To see how much information was lost in the=
 compression we can measure the image=E2=80=99s <strong>reconstruction erro=
r</strong>. We will measure the reconstruction error as the mean of squared=
 errors (MSE) between the the pixel values of the original image and the re=
constructed image.</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">In Scikit-Learn, the reconstructed image ca=
n be obtained by calling the method <code>inverse_transform</code> of the <=
code>TruncatedSVD</code> transformer:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">reconstructed_image <span class=3D"token opera=
tor">=3D</span> svd<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>inverse_transf=
orm<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>truncated_image<span class=3D"=
token punctuation">)</span></code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Therefore, the reconstruction error is:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">reconstruction_error =3D np.mean(np.squa=
re(reconstructed_image - flat_image))
reconstruction_error</code></pre>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-none" tabindex=3D"0"><code=
 class=3D"language- language-none">29.323291415822336</code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">Thus, the root mean squared error (RMSE) be=
tween the pixel intensities in the original image and the reconstructed ima=
ge is only about 5.41 (which is small relative to the range of the pixels [=
0, 255]).</p>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">To display the reconstructed image, we firs=
t need to reshape it into the original 3D shape and then clip the pixel val=
ues to integers in the range [0, 255]:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">reconstructed_image <span class=3D"token opera=
tor">=3D</span> reconstructed_image<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</spa=
n>reshape<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>height<span class=3D"tok=
en punctuation">,</span> width<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> ch=
annels<span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
reconstructed_image <span class=3D"token operator">=3D</span> np<span class=
=3D"token punctuation">.</span>clip<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</spa=
n>reconstructed_image<span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <span class=
=3D"token number">0</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">,</span> <span =
class=3D"token number">255</span><span class=3D"token punctuation">)</span>=
<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>astype<span class=3D"token punctu=
ation">(</span><span class=3D"token string">'uint8'</span><span class=3D"to=
ken punctuation">)</span></code></pre>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We can now display the image using the <cod=
e>plt.imshow</code> function:</p>
<pre class=3D"wp-block-prismatic-blocks language-python" tabindex=3D"0"><co=
de class=3D"language-python">plt<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>i=
mshow<span class=3D"token punctuation">(</span>reconstructed_image<span cla=
ss=3D"token punctuation">)</span>
plt<span class=3D"token punctuation">.</span>axis<span class=3D"token punct=
uation">(</span><span class=3D"token string">'off'</span><span class=3D"tok=
en punctuation">)</span></code></pre>
<figure class=3D"wp-block-image size-large"><img data-dominant-color=3D"cec=
3bb" data-has-transparency=3D"true" style=3D"--dominant-color: #cec3bb;" lo=
ading=3D"lazy" decoding=3D"async" width=3D"1513" height=3D"890" class=3D"wp=
-image-508508 has-transparency" src=3D"https://towardsdatascience.com/wp-co=
ntent/uploads/2023/11/1suo03oJg-cJ_9zGtmr6QRg.png" alt=3D"The reconstructed=
 image"><figcaption class=3D"wp-element-caption">The reconstructed image</f=
igcaption></figure>
<p class=3D"wp-block-paragraph">We can see that the reconstruction at rank =
100 loses only a small amount of detail.</p>
